Is SpaceX really going to hop SN5 with just one Raptor engine, and if so, why? Surely it will be a compelling stress test, and a compelling performance test, not to mention a real world opportunity for systems diagnostics. However; and maybe this is just my OCD acting up, but, it seems like a 150 meter hop test using one engine puts uneven wear and tare on both SN5 and the raptor engine.

Why not put two more raptors on so that the weight can be evenly distributed, the way it will be according to specs. Either that; or, if they are going to use just one engine, why don't they attach it at the center of SN5's base, the way the engine was attached on Star Hopper? I suppose that would require some temporary modifications to make the attachment, but, it it seems doable. For the hell of it; they could then detach that Raptor, and conduct two more 150 meter hops with two more Raptor engines so that if SN5 is viable, they can finish building it with engines that are evenly worn.

Like I said; I have no doubt that they know what they're doing, so maybe I'm making much Ado about nothing, but, for me, it would just feel right to know that SN5 would come off the assembly line, with any and all stress testing being more or less evenly distributed, so that, from stem to stern, SN5, is in tip-top shape. No unnecessary bends or warps in the structure. Ya'know. I don't know, I hope that makes sense.

Just my thoughts. Anyways, carry on.
